# unit - Rust

## Primitive Type [unit](#)

1.0.0 ยท

Expand description

The `()` type, also called โunitโ.

The `()` type has exactly one value `()`, and is used when there is no other meaningful value that could be returned. `()` is most commonly seen implicitly: functions without a `-> ...` implicitly have return type `()`, that is, these are equivalent:

```
fn long() -> () {}

fn short() {}
```

[Run](https://play.rust-lang.org/?code=%23!%5Ballow(unused)%5D%0Afn+main()+%7B%0A++++fn+long()+-%3E+()+%7B%7D%0A++++%0A++++fn+short()+%7B%7D%0A%7D&edition=2021)

The semicolon `;` can be used to discard the result of an expression at the end of a block, making the expression (and thus the block) evaluate to `()`. For example,

```
fn returns_i64() -> i64 {
    1i64
}
fn returns_unit() {
    1i64;
}

let is_i64 = {
    returns_i64()
};
let is_unit = {
    returns_i64();
};
```

[Run](https://play.rust-lang.org/?code=%23!%5Ballow(unused)%5D%0Afn+main()+%7B%0A++++fn+returns_i64()+-%3E+i64+%7B%0A++++++++1i64%0A++++%7D%0A++++fn+returns_unit()+%7B%0A++++++++1i64;%0A++++%7D%0A++++%0A++++let+is_i64+=+%7B%0A++++++++returns_i64()%0A++++%7D;%0A++++let+is_unit+=+%7B%0A++++++++returns_i64();%0A++++%7D;%0A%7D&edition=2021)

1.23.0 ยท [source](https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.80.0/src/core/unit.rs.html#15)[ยง](#impl-FromIterator%3C()%3E-for-())

Collapses all unit items from an iterator into one.

This is more useful when combined with higher-level abstractions, like collecting to a `Result<(), E>` where you only care about errors:

```
use std::io::*;
let data = vec![1, 2, 3, 4, 5];
let res: Result<()> = data.iter()
    .map(|x| writeln!(stdout(), "{x}"))
    .collect();
assert!(res.is_ok());
```

[Run](https://play.rust-lang.org/?code=%23!%5Ballow(unused)%5D%0Afn+main()+%7B%0A++++use+std::io::*;%0A++++let+data+=+vec!%5B1,+2,+3,+4,+5%5D;%0A++++let+res:+Result%3C()%3E+=+data.iter()%0A++++++++.map(%7Cx%7C+writeln!(stdout(),+%22%7Bx%7D%22))%0A++++++++.collect();%0A++++assert!(res.is_ok());%0A%7D&edition=2021)
